Lab 1: Introduction to AWS IAM – Summary
In this lab, I learned how AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM) is used to control access to AWS resources. I began by accessing the AWS Management Console and navigating to the IAM service, where I explored pre-created users (user-1, user-2, and user-3) and observed that they initially had no permissions or group memberships. I also examined existing IAM groups (EC2-Admin, EC2-Support, and S3-Support) and reviewed their attached policies, including managed policies like AmazonEC2ReadOnlyAccess and AmazonS3ReadOnlyAccess, as well as an inline policy that allowed EC2 instance control.
Next, I followed a business scenario to assign users to groups based on their job roles. I added user-1 to the S3-Support group, user-2 to the EC2-Support group, and user-3 to the EC2-Admin group. This demonstrated how permissions are inherited through group membership rather than being assigned directly to users, which simplifies access management and follows best practices.
After configuring the groups, I tested each user’s permissions by signing in through the IAM sign-in URL using a private browser session. As user-1, I confirmed read-only access to Amazon S3 and verified that EC2 access was denied. As user-2, I was able to view EC2 instances but could not stop them, confirming read-only permissions, and I was denied access to S3. As user-3, I successfully stopped an EC2 instance, demonstrating elevated administrative permissions.
Overall, this lab showed how IAM users, groups, and policies work together to enforce role-based access control. It reinforced the principle of least privilege by assigning only the permissions necessary for each role and demonstrated how AWS manages secure access through centralized identity management.
